#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
gemini-ncurses-python

Full-screen Python ncurses implementation for gemini-terminal-tools.

MAINTAINER COMMENTARY
=====================
This source file is intentionally verbose.  The comments are not here merely to
teach Python or curses; they are here to future-proof the project.  A terminal
AI client depends on several moving parts that may change independently: Google
model names, the Gemini REST schema, terminal emulator behavior, ncurses mouse
semantics, filesystem layout, user config expectations, and the project's own
parallel Bash/C implementations.  When one of those parts changes, maintainers
need to understand why the code is shaped the way it is before they safely patch
it.

The Python ncurses version is the behavioral reference implementation for the
future native C ncurses version.  That means this file should remain readable to
people who may not want to preserve the Python code exactly, but who do need to
copy the design: session logs, rolling context memory, model list caching,
user-operated model testing, attachment conventions, file browsing, editor
integration, and global function-key navigation.

The design posture is deliberately end-user oriented.  This is not a developer
curl example and not an SDK demonstration.  The program's job is to let people
use AI productively from a terminal without a browser.  If a feature forces the
user to think like an API developer, that feature should probably be wrapped in
a menu, a status explanation, or a diagnostic screen.

Several implementation choices in this file are conservative on purpose:

* The config format is simple KEY=VALUE so the Bash versions and future C
  version can share it without a heavy parser.
* Model selection is metadata-driven and user-operated.  The program should not
  automatically probe every model.  It lists models, filters metadata, lets the
  user inspect/test one model, and then lets the user activate/save it.
* Logs are plain text because they must be greppable, recoverable, and readable
  even if this program stops working.
* Memory snapshots are saved into logs so a resumed session can regain context.
* Generated/code attachments are saved as files because a terminal workflow is
  strongest when artifacts become ordinary filesystem objects.
* Function keys are treated as global navigation.  A user should not get trapped
  in a modal screen after hitting the wrong key.

If you fork this project, preserve these ideas unless you are deliberately
changing the product philosophy.  If you maintain this project, prefer clear
state transitions, explicit user consent for network actions, and comments that
explain design intent rather than only restating the syntax.
"""

